        What Happens to the Deposit if a Queensland Property Sale Falls Through 2027?
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Whether the seller keeps the deposit depends entirely on why the sale did not proceed. Here is how Queensland property deposits work and what your rights are if a contract falls over.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>When a property sale falls through, the deposit question is usually the first thing vendors ask about. The answer in Queensland is not one-size-fits-all. What happens to the deposit depends entirely on the circumstances under which the contract ended: who terminated, when they terminated, and whether the termination was a lawful exercise of a contract condition or a default by the buyer.</p>

      <p>Understanding the different scenarios clearly before you sign a contract helps you approach the sale with realistic expectations and make better decisions if a deal does fall over.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How deposits work in Queensland</h2>
      <p>In a standard Queensland residential property sale, the buyer pays a deposit on or shortly after signing the contract. The deposit is typically 10% of the purchase price, though a lower initial deposit (sometimes referred to as an initial deposit or holding deposit) followed by a balance deposit is also common. The contract and the REIQ Contract for Houses and Residential Land set out when each payment is due.</p>

      <p>The deposit is paid into a trust account held by either the real estate agent or the seller's solicitor. It is held in trust until settlement, at which point it forms part of the purchase price paid to the vendor. The money is not the seller's to use during the period between contract and settlement: it sits in trust and can only be released in specific circumstances.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Cooling-off period termination: buyer loses 0.25%</h2>
      <p>Queensland residential property contracts are subject to a five-business-day cooling-off period for buyers. If the buyer exercises their cooling-off right and terminates the contract during this period, they are entitled to a refund of the deposit, but not a full refund. The seller is entitled to retain 0.25% of the purchase price as a cooling-off penalty.</p>

      <p>On a $1,000,000 property, the cooling-off penalty is $2,500. The remaining deposit is returned to the buyer. The 0.25% penalty is the seller's only entitlement in a cooling-off termination, regardless of any costs the seller has incurred (preparing documents, taking the property off the market, refusing other offers). There is no negotiation on this figure: it is set by legislation.</p>

      <p>Auctions are not subject to the cooling-off period: a contract formed at auction is unconditional from exchange and the buyer has no cooling-off right.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Failed finance condition: deposit returned in full</h2>
      <p>Most private treaty sales in Queensland are signed with finance and building and pest inspection conditions. If the buyer terminates the contract because their finance application was genuinely not approved, and they terminate within the finance condition period stated in the contract, the deposit must be returned to them in full. The seller has no entitlement to any part of the deposit in this scenario.</p>

      <p>The same applies to a building and pest inspection condition: if the buyer obtains an unsatisfactory inspection report and exercises their right to terminate under that condition within the specified period, the full deposit is returned. The seller cannot challenge the buyer's entitlement to terminate if the termination is a valid exercise of a contract condition.</p>

      <p>This is why the terms of conditions in your contract matter. A finance condition with a five-day period protects the buyer for five days. A finance condition that has a shorter period, or a contract where the parties have agreed to waive the finance condition, produces a different outcome if the buyer's finance does not come through.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Buyer default after going unconditional: deposit forfeited</h2>
      <p>If the contract becomes unconditional, meaning all conditions have been satisfied or waived, and the buyer then fails to proceed to settlement, the situation changes significantly in the seller's favour. A buyer who defaults on an unconditional contract is in breach, and the seller's rights in that situation are considerably stronger.</p>

      <p>The seller must follow the correct process to terminate the contract and forfeit the deposit. Under the Property Law Act 1974 (Qld) and the contract terms, this typically involves serving a notice to complete, which gives the buyer a final deadline to complete the purchase. If the buyer fails to settle by the date in the notice to complete, the seller can terminate the contract and elect to forfeit the deposit.</p>

      <p>After termination, the deposit does not automatically land in the seller's account. It is still held in trust, and there is a formal process for releasing it to the seller. The trustee holding the deposit (the agent or solicitor) must be instructed to release it, and the buyer must either consent or the seller must follow the process for releasing the deposit over the buyer's objection. In practice, this usually means waiting a period of time and following the procedures set out in the relevant legislation, or obtaining a court order if the buyer contests the forfeiture.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Beyond the deposit: when sellers can claim damages</h2>
      <p>If the deposit does not cover the seller's actual loss from a buyer default, the seller may have a claim for damages in addition to forfeiting the deposit. If the seller has to re-list the property and ultimately sells it for less than the original contract price, the shortfall (plus carrying costs between the original settlement date and the resale settlement) represents recoverable loss over and above the deposit.</p>

      <p>Whether it is worth pursuing a damages claim depends on the size of the loss, the buyer's financial position, and the cost of litigation. A buyer who has defaulted on a contract may have no assets worth pursuing, in which case a successful damages judgment produces nothing in practice. Getting realistic legal advice early is important: your solicitor can assess the buyer's position and advise whether a claim is worth pursuing before you spend money on proceedings.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers should factor in when deciding whether to pursue a defaulting buyer</h2>
      <p>The decision to pursue a defaulting buyer is not just a legal calculation. It is also a timing and commercial decision. While proceedings are underway, your ability to re-list the property may be constrained or complicated. A dispute over the deposit or a damages claim can take months to resolve, during which time the market may move. Many sellers decide that forfeiting the deposit, ending the contract cleanly, and re-listing promptly is a better outcome than a prolonged dispute, even if the legal position would support a larger recovery.</p>

      <p>Your solicitor should walk you through the scenarios before you make any decisions: how much is at stake, how long recovery will take, what the buyer appears to be able to pay, and what the real estate market looks like for your property right now. Knowing what the property would realistically achieve if re-listed today is a key input into that decision, which is where your agent's market knowledge becomes relevant again.</p>

